column11: Update - added the color blocks for the discrete trait in pair view. I’m going to add the calculations in there next. Website is updated if you wanted to see what it looks like! Also - talked to Alex and he is wondering how we can make a case study that includes the summary view. Any ideas what else the summary view needs to make it usable? I added the copy functionality from the brush selection but need to add in the highlighting of outliers
column12: Awesome! I'll try to check it out soon. And I'll need to think about the summary view. The only think I could think of would be to show a summary of traits for each ecomorph - that really is more of just a general tool to look at/view the data. But I'll mull it over and see if I can't think of anything.

column2: Update with AP on Path View
column11: Update - added indication of outliers to the summary view. Also I was thinking - you can define groups of species now from discrete or continuous traits. Maybe a use case for that view would be to define groups by ecomorph category and check to see how the distributions differ from the entire tree / other ectomorph groups? I’ll send an email with more info to you and LH!
column12: Yeah, I think that woul dbe perfect! That way you can see, directly from the data, how, and among which traits each group differs. I like it!
column15: One thing I noticed the other night is that a lot of the convergent pairs are not both the same ecomorph - but because we are looking at a single trait, would it make sense that two ectomorphs would have similar characteristics for a single trait? Ex: trunk crown and twig having similar “PCIII_Padwitch_vs_tail”?
column16: Hmmmm.... You're finding that even when using the PC traits? Because those PCs are essentially composites of multiple traits
column17: For the island anolis data yes, I thought twig and trunk crowns had longer tails and larger toe pads though?
column18: Okay. For all of them? Or only pc 3? How many species are you finding convergent among groups? I mean, it's not necessarily an issue - these ecomorphs are defined in a real broad way, and they often overlap in pc space. Yeah, they do. So when looking along one or two trait axes, we SHOULD find overlaps among groups. That's where potentially doing this across traits and looking at those that are enriched for convergent trait instances would be valuable. Looking across traits like that could give us a better sense of whole body convergence.
column19: That makes sense - I might relook at the algorithm that calculates the scores too just in case! I have the heat map visualization on the right that shows the other traits that it scores top 1% in so I can sort by that. Putting the top pairs that are convergent in more than one trait on the top. THINK I FOUND A BUG IN THE DELTA.
column21: Should be an easy fix I’ll just bin diffs by time and get max bin stand by haha
column22: Okay - what was it doing before?
column23: I just looked at the code and I have been binning. That max delta for the top pair doesn’t look like it’s larger than the max for the second. Im digging around to figure out why.
